There's definitely more to it than that. What country you live in will affect your path forward with aerial work. If you're an American like me you have to study for your Part 107 FAA Airman's certification, study sectional charts, weather, aviation principles, and then pass the test with an FAA certified proctor, then you have to buy a drone (you're spending minimum $1,500 for a professional-quality machine), get it insured, and register the thing with the FAA. Then you have to really know what airspaces are legal to practice and work in, and how to get the proper clearances to do so. Say you have a client who needs you to take pictures of their house. But they live near a Class B airport? Gotta fill out an LAANC request for that shoot.

Honestly thoguh it was tons of fun just progressing throguh all that stuff and by the end of it you can make $200/hr doing real estate phototherapy, plus you can charge for your time editing photos and videos, and their are other lucrative subfields to explore like GIS mapping, building inspections, agricultural applications, movie production, etc. Fuck I know guys who rake in $10k/Day sitting on a movie set on standby just in case the director wants to get an aerial shot. If you go in the direction of film production you can also join IATSE Local 600 since it's considered a camera platform and it's one of the best locals to be a part of. Honestly anon it's like anything, if you're passionate and excited enough by a field you like, you'll go far.

I did it also because lighting is backbreaking work and inwanted to get into a more technical/crestive field that was kinder on my body. Flying robots and taking pretty pictures with them just makes my heart sing and it also brings in the cash without fucking up my knees. If you're really interested in something then set your mind to it and do it.', 'time': 1670759589, 'resto': 27893213}]

name: Anonymous
com: I've been at it for almost five years, and while it felt good at first, not anymore. I'm scared of balding, I might get caught and be disowned by my family, and it's just a waste of time. Any advice?
last_replies:
[{'no': 27894252, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)01:09:05', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'just stop gripping your dick bro', 'filename': 'ather', 'ext': '.jpg', 'w': 540, 'h': 540, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 125, 'tim': 1670738945374954, 'time': 1670738945, 'md5': 'K5nvrGCs1YTE+TeEV1Hp0Q==', 'fsize': 27213, 'resto': 27894212}, {'no': 27894374, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)01:40:39', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>27894212
The reason you can’t stop is because we are complex entities. You get in one mood, and you want desperately to stop. You get in another, maybe you feel like nothing matters anyway, and you just watch it. Or you get in another mood where you feel like you’ve overcome it, and think you can watch it to prove that you’ve overcome it.

There’s not just 1 or 2. It’s complex. And you need to look at those moods, and become as familiar with them as you are with happy and sad.

Then you need to study how they arise. How you get into them. How do you tend to think, and what are the underlying beliefs of each of those moods? Where does it tend to lead you? What sort of life is it creating?

You’re trying to BEGIN with the conclusion that you you should quit, which is probably true, but you get into moods where you don’t believe it. Force / strong will can’t get you through it, because in a different mood, you have a different will. Rather you have to establish a meta-knowledge of yourself, because then your will can finally become overarching.

So look at yourself clearly enough, as I described, and if quitting porn becomes your genuine conclusion, then it’ll be extremely easy. The thing that doesn’t work is telling yourself you don’t even want it, because there’s going to come a time and place where you do want it. That’s just setting yourself up for failure. You have to be willing to truly look at what’s going on. If you’re not willing to give up on the objective of quitting, then let that be your anchor as you look more honestly at yourself. And let it be the source of the motivation to actually study it, because there is no way around it. If you are serious, then saying that you want to quit is the same thing as saying that you want to study these things.', 'time': 1670740839, 'resto': 27894212}, {'no': 27894605, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)03:01:48', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>27894212
Have a tripwire.

Mine is when I am horny, I have sex with my wife.', 'time': 1670745708, 'resto': 27894212}, {'no': 27894797, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)04:44:02', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>27894374

Second to that is my interest in medicine/humanitarian work, particularly phlebotomy.

Want a career in the military first, medical stuff is second. Which branch would you recommend?
last_replies:
[{'no': 27894696, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)03:52:23', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>27894672
If you want to enlist then the Navy is a decent option. The nice thing about being a Hospital Corpsman is the versatility. You can serve almost anywhere stateside, overseas, on a ship, on land, wherever. The option to specialize is there with some 30 different specialties available, with options like nuclear medicine, behavioral health, field medical and much more. As a Corpsman you will have lots of opportunities to practice phlebotomy and a whole lot else. If you can think of it, chances are there's an opportunity to do it as an HM.

Officer side I don't know as I was never one. Do you have any specific questions? I might be able to give you better info if so.', 'time': 1670748743, 'resto': 27894672}, {'no': 27894803, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)04:46:44', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>27894696
Thanks for the info anon, and yeah that is a crazy amount of options. I'm definitely more interested in the versatility.

I am wondering, I've done a semester of community college, will that mean I would lose out on college paid tuition?

Also when it comes to nuclear medicine, the hell is that like?', 'time': 1670752004, 'resto': 27894672}, {'no': 27894867, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)05:18:09', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>27894803
It shouldn't, no. Tuition assistance should be available for you while you are active duty provide your chain of command is willing to sign off on it (just do your job and don't be a shitbag and you should be good to go), and provided you get an honorable discharge the GI bill will be there after you get out. There are other edu benefits too but I don't know much about them.

Nuke med is stuff like xray. Check out the HM page on the Navy website and Navy COOL to learn more specifics about the various NECs. Be forewarned though, aside from dental technician I don't believe you can get an NEC (specialty like nuke med) guaranteed in your contract. So, you may end up not doing the exact job you want, at least for a while. But, you can apply for a c school later on if it's not available once you graduate your initial trainings. Note that after you acquire a speciality it can be hard to move from it, with the exception of field medical tech but it's not really a "normal" speciality, rather it's an extention of your basic abilities that enables you to serve with operational units including USMC commands.

I wad a basic (0000) and field med (8404) guy so that's where my experience lies. Any other questions?', 'time': 1670753889, 'resto': 27894672}]

I can only speak for myself, and maybe I’m projecting but from my experience and from the friends and loved ones who are around my age? 20’s is gonna have a massive rainstorm of the soul. It does for a lot of people. A LOT. It’s why most people in misery posting on /adv/ are ages 18 - 25 mostly.

>Does life get any better?
Yes. 110%. Once your brain stops developing at 25 and you find your bearings by your late 20’s—by the time you’re 30 you will ‘grow into yourself’. Things will feel better, or, more tolerable. Alright, so a little background setting,

So, I came from a pretty poor upbringing. Lots of social isolation, neglect. Incredibly poor. Near homeless; shit like that. Not going to go much further because I'm not here to tell a sob story -- want to focus on today.

Despite upbringing circumstances, I've somehow managed to land myself well off in life. I work for a smaller enterprise focused company making over six figures a year. I've no debt, aside from my mortgage, which is very low interest and around ~13% of my gross income. I'm married, but no kids yet.

I max my retirement accounts, I have a reasonable crypto slush fund.

While it's all well and good, all of my income and quality of life today is 100% based on my primary job. I have quite a few thousand in the bank and could easily invest in side-ventures; but I continue to struggle to stay committed to anything long enough to actually start pursuing side businesses.

I always talk myself out of everything. I come from a background of Enterprise Support, Backend Software, and Product. I could easily run a small business myself -- but I never can identify a clear target market or stick with a project as I'm too pessimistic. "Nobody will buy this; this will take too much marketing; this is too manual", etc, etc.

I find I end up defeating myself pre-emptively and just end up playing video games or watching TV with my spare time. I'm always fearful this job won't last forever (especially in this economy), and I really want to start venturing out but I always feel blocked

What's a good way to work on this motivation? Even better if anyone has any ideas on where to pursue ideas?
I'm willing to put money into the side venture; so starting capital isn't an issue; it's ironically all the rest.
